                <div class="tab-content">
                    <div class="tab-pane active" id="tab-script">
                        <div class="js-script-content-wrapper top-margin-script markdown-content">
                                                                                        <a href="https://github.com/knpuniversity/stripe/edit/master/knpu/ep2-subscriptions/monthly-to-yearly.md" target="_blank" class="btn btn-default btn-circle pull-right js-tooltip" title="Edit on GitHub"><span class="fa fa-pencil"></span></a>
                                                                    <p>So far, we <em>only</em> offer monthly plans. But sheep <em>love</em> commitment, so they've been
asking for <em>yearly</em> options. Well, great news! After all that upgrade stuff we
just handled, this is going to be <em>easy</em>.</p>
<h2 id="creating-the-new-plans">Creating the New Plans <a class="headerlink" href="monthly-to-yearly#creating-the-new-plans" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>First, in Stripe's dashboard, we need to create two new plans. Call the first
"Farmer Brent yearly" and for the total... how about 99 X 10: so $990, per year.</p>
<p>Then, add the New Zealander yearly, set to 1990, billed yearly.</p>
<p>Cool! I'm not going to update our checkout to allow these plans initially, because,
honestly, that's super easy: just create some new links to add these plans to your
cart, and you're done.</p>
<p>Nope, we'll skip straight to the hard stuff: allowing the user to <em>change</em> between
monthly and yearly plans.</p>
<h2 id="adding-the-subscriptionplan-objects">Adding the SubscriptionPlan Objects <a class="headerlink" href="monthly-to-yearly#adding-the-subscriptionplan-objects" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>First, we need to add these plans to our system. Open the <code>SubscriptionPlan</code> class.
To distinguish between monthly and yearly plans, add a new property called <code>duration</code>:
this will be a string, either <code>monthly</code> or <code>yearly</code>. At the top, I love constants,
so create: <code>const DURATION_MONTHLY = 'monthly'</code> and <code>const DURATION_YEARLY = 'yearly'</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="2a33c879a6">
